00:14:08,400 --> 00:14:10,600
I thought Abby was smarter than that.

254
00:14:10,680 --> 00:14:12,680
Hoffman's cool. He's a sharp dude.

255
00:14:12,760 --> 00:14:14,880
I saw some of his articles.

256
00:14:14,960 --> 00:14:16,560
It's some deep shit, man.

257
00:14:16,640 --> 00:14:18,160
It put me right to sleep.

258
00:14:18,240 --> 00:14:21,720
It's just... It's just
bad judgment on Abby's part,

259
00:14:21,800 --> 00:14:22,880
you know what I'm saying?

260
00:14:22,960 --> 00:14:24,360
She's too young for you, man.

261
00:14:24,440 --> 00:14:26,160
Hey, take it easy, will you?

262
00:14:26,200 --> 00:14:27,920
<i>[James]
Hoffman heading out.</i>

263
00:14:27,960 --> 00:14:29,960
[door creaking open]

264
00:14:30,040 --> 00:14:31,360
[door closing]

265
00:14:35,560 --> 00:14:37,760
How long have they been
at it, Abby and him?

266
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:43,280
I don't know, man. Ask her.

267
00:14:43,320 --> 00:14:44,720
Hand me that Allen wrench,
will you, boss?

268
00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:46,160
How long?

269
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:47,800
Three to four weeks.

270
00:14:49,320 --> 00:14:52,560
It won't last. I'll tell you that much.

271
00:14:52,640 --> 00:14:55,360
I guess he just got lucky.

272
00:14:57,360 --> 00:14:58,560
Here's his thing, you know,

273
00:14:58,640 --> 00:14:59,920
if you want to check it out.

274
00:15:03,920 --> 00:15:05,920
[Ed]
Yeah, this guy's seen it all, hasn't he?

275
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:07,920
[Motor]
That's him.

276
00:15:10,200 --> 00:15:13,840
Thanks for the Allen wrench,
by the way.

277
00:15:13,920 --> 00:15:16,360
I mean, North thinks
they can win a PR campaign,

278
00:15:16,400 --> 00:15:18,760
hiring greenies to do
the impact statements.

279
00:15:18,840 --> 00:15:20,000
It's a waste of money, you know?

280
00:15:20,080 --> 00:15:22,200
The public is with us on this.

281
00:15:22,280 --> 00:15:23,160
They can see the potential.

282
00:15:23,240 --> 00:15:26,280
They don't need to get bogged down
with a lot of hand wringing.

283
00:15:26,320 --> 00:15:29,680
He thinks there's something off-kilter
going on out here.

284
00:15:29,760 --> 00:15:31,000
Is that what he's telling everybody?

285
00:15:31,080 --> 00:15:32,400
Yeah, the permafrost is melting.

286
00:15:32,480 --> 00:15:35,880
That's what he says.

287
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:38,720
Haven't you smelled it?

288
00:15:38,800 --> 00:15:40,360
Fucking dick.

289
00:16:44,080 --> 00:16:49,520
<i>[James]
Saturday, week 9.</i>

290
00:16:49,560 --> 00:16:53,840
<i>Radical temperature rises
continues from last week.</i>

291
00:16:53,920 --> 00:16:55,880
<i>Since blizzard of February 7th,</i>

292
00:16:55,960 --> 00:16:57,720
<i>low of 15 Fahrenheit.</i>

293
00:16:57,800 --> 00:16:59,360
<i>Temperature on consistent rise</i>

294
00:16:59,440 --> 00:17:02,000
<i>with seven day
average of 31 degrees.</i>

295
00:17:02,040 --> 00:17:06,320
<i>High of 36 on February 12th.</i>

296
00:17:06,360 --> 00:17:08,680
<i>Anecdotal weather
fluctuations continue,</i>

297
00:17:08,720 --> 00:17:11,120
<i>with consistent sub-surface warming.</i>

298
00:17:11,160 --> 00:17:14,120
Ground reading's 3 to 7 degrees

299
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:15,520
increase over same week.

300
00:17:15,600 --> 00:17:20,680
Same quadrant average of last five years.

301
00:17:21,760 --> 00:17:23,760
[cawing]

302
00:17:23,840 --> 00:17:24,840
It's you again.

303
00:17:27,920 --> 00:17:30,440
Mess up all my stuff, hmm?

304
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:31,920
Is that you?

305
00:17:39,840 --> 00:17:42,920
<i>- Beggar.
- Something up here is off.</i>

306
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:45,520
<i>It's in the numbers, but also I can feel it.</i>

307
00:18:12,240 --> 00:18:13,200
[wings flapping]

308
00:18:20,720 --> 00:18:22,000
<i>[radio chatter]</i>

309
00:18:26,160 --> 00:18:27,920
Maxwell, over.

310
00:18:27,960 --> 00:18:30,200
[radio feedback]

311
00:18:30,280 --> 00:18:32,800
<i>[indistinct dialogue, static]</i>

312
00:18:32,880 --> 00:18:34,120
[radio clicks off]

313
00:18:58,480 --> 00:19:00,480
[rumbling]

314
00:19:48,840 --> 00:19:51,280
I don't know why they don't
just lay tarmac down

315
00:19:51,360 --> 00:19:52,560
at the start of these projects

316
00:19:52,640 --> 00:19:55,160
instead of fucking around
with these ice roads.

317
00:19:55,240 --> 00:19:58,960
That would be a violation of the terms
that got North Industries onto this land.

318
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:00,200
Yeah, yeah.

319
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:02,840
Well, my only concern
is getting my equipment in.

320
00:20:02,920 --> 00:20:07,520
My only recommendation is that we wait
for a sustained temperature drop.

321
00:20:08,720 --> 00:20:09,800
I'll tell you what.

322
00:20:09,880 --> 00:20:11,240
Change of plans.

323
00:20:11,280 --> 00:20:13,920
We're gonna bring the rigs in on rollagons.

324
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:15,520
Rollagons?

325
00:20:15,600 --> 00:20:16,720
Has that been approved?

326
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:18,480
Everybody's behind it back at the office.

327
00:20:18,560 --> 00:20:20,760
Nobody wants to miss the season.

328
00:20:20,840 --> 00:20:22,360
That's going to be very expensive.

329
00:20:22,440 --> 00:20:25,160
Rollagons would cause
serious damage to the tundra

330
00:20:25,200 --> 00:20:27,000
with the temperatures this high.

331
00:20:27,080 --> 00:20:30,280
Well, luckily I don't have to have this
discussion with you.

332
00:20:30,320 --> 00:20:31,840
I need Hoffman. Where the fuck is he?

333
00:20:31,920 --> 00:20:33,280
I don't know.

334
00:20:33,360 --> 00:20:34,480
He was coming right back.

335
00:20:34,520 --> 00:20:36,040
Well, I need for him to sign off on this.

336
00:20:36,120 --> 00:20:37,360
This is what I came back here for.

337
00:20:37,400 --> 00:20:38,840
We should be careful
how we handle that.

338
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:41,800
Hey, Motor, what's up?
We're a little busy here.

339
00:20:41,880 --> 00:20:43,680
Maxwell's not back yet. I'm worried.

340
00:20:43,760 --> 00:20:45,240
The Ski-Doo is acting up.

341
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:47,880
Maybe it copped out on him.

342
00:20:56,720 --> 00:20:57,840
Hey, Abby, what's going on?

343
00:20:57,920 --> 00:20:59,280
Where the hell have you been?

344
00:20:59,320 --> 00:21:00,960
Maxwell's not back.
He's not answering the walkie.

345
00:21:01,040 --> 00:21:02,240
He's not answering?

346
00:21:02,320 --> 00:21:03,280
Do you need any help?

347
00:21:03,360 --> 00:21:04,760
I wouldn't worry about Maxwell.

348
00:21:04,840 --> 00:21:06,960
The kid could walk from here
to Vegas on his hands.

349
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:08,760
- Maxwell, do you read?
- Where have you been?

350
00:21:08,840 --> 00:21:12,960
So you guys didn't get
any kind of a sudden wind down here?

351
00:21:13,040 --> 00:21:14,160
Anything strange like that happen?

352
00:21:14,240 --> 00:21:15,440
[Ed]
Yeah.

353
00:21:15,520 --> 00:21:17,680
Yeah, we had a meeting,
and you never showed up.

354
00:21:17,760 --> 00:21:19,880
That was strange.

355
00:21:19,920 --> 00:21:22,200
[Abby]
Lee, let's go!

356
00:21:22,280 --> 00:21:24,560
[snowmobile engine starting]

357
00:21:24,640 --> 00:21:25,640
[engine revving]

358
00:21:36,360 --> 00:21:39,920
Look, I am sorry about being late.

359
00:21:42,400 --> 00:21:44,000
We need to talk, you and me.

360
00:21:44,080 --> 00:21:45,240
We don't need the others.

361
00:21:48,800 --> 00:21:50,200
Hoffman, I don't know you,

362
00:21:50,280 --> 00:21:53,840
and I'm not going to try to handle this
with some diplomatic mumbo jumbo.

363
00:21:53,920 --> 00:21:58,240
I'm just going to tell you what I need,
and I'm going to expect you to deliver.

364
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:01,520
Go ahead.

365
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:04,160
I got environmental impact statements
I need you to sign,

366
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:06,680
saying we can bring
the rigs in a rollagons.

367
00:22:06,760 --> 00:22:07,640
What?

368
00:22:07,720 --> 00:22:09,560
The ice roads aren't working.

369
00:22:09,640 --> 00:22:11,000
It's what we gotta do.

370
00:22:14,280 --> 00:22:15,760
[flipping page]

371
00:22:20,920 --> 00:22:22,520
<i>Okay.</i>

372
00:22:25,640 --> 00:22:27,320
What, is that a yes?

373
00:22:29,520 --> 00:22:30,680
I'll look at your proposal.

374
00:22:30,760 --> 00:22:33,480
It's not a proposal.

375
00:22:33,520 --> 00:22:37,000
It's an okay I need you to sign.

376
00:22:38,280 --> 00:22:42,320
Ed, I'm not going to sign something
just because you need me to.

377
00:22:45,240 --> 00:22:47,480
I think we should make
sure Maxwell's back safe

378
00:22:47,560 --> 00:22:49,240
before we get into this.

379
00:22:54,280 --> 00:22:57,440
[door opening]

380
00:22:57,520 --> 00:22:59,520
[door closing]

381
00:23:05,200 --> 00:23:10,200
[Ed]
Foster, yeah, he's not biting.

382
00:23:10,280 --> 00:23:14,480
Yeah. Yeah?

383
00:23:14,520 --> 00:23:16,400
We should go through with that.

384
00:23:35,800 --> 00:23:36,880
There you go.

385
00:23:37,840 --> 00:23:38,840
You should call her.

386
00:23:38,920 --> 00:23:41,360
I just tried. Nothing.

387
00:23:41,440 --> 00:23:42,480
These things ever work?

388
00:23:42,560 --> 00:23:46,120
Maxwell was bound to get lost eventually.

389
00:23:46,160 --> 00:23:48,720
Is that right?

390
00:23:50,520 --> 00:23:52,240
He seems overwhelmed.

391
00:23:52,320 --> 00:23:55,600
This whole damn operation
needs an attitude adjustment.

392
00:23:55,640 --> 00:23:56,760
It's unacceptable.

393
00:23:56,840 --> 00:23:58,720
<i>[indistinct radio chatter]</i>

394
00:23:58,800 --> 00:24:00,200
Go ahead.

395
00:24:00,240 --> 00:24:02,560
<i>[static]</i>

396
00:24:02,640 --> 00:24:04,280
Hello?

397
00:24:04,360 --> 00:24:07,120
[phone rings]

398
00:24:07,160 --> 00:24:08,320
Hmm.

399
00:24:09,520 --> 00:24:11,760
[ring]

400
00:24:13,160 --> 00:24:14,600
Pollack here.

401
00:24:14,680 --> 00:24:16,600
[Ed]
Hoffman?

402
00:24:16,680 --> 00:24:18,120
No, he's here.

403
00:24:18,200 --> 00:24:20,240
Yeah. Hang on.

404
00:24:20,320 --> 00:24:21,280
Hoffman!

405
00:24:24,760 --> 00:24:25,800
Hoffman!

406
00:24:30,520 --> 00:24:32,040
Foster's on the line.

407
00:24:32,120 --> 00:24:34,600
Make it quick, will you?

408
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:35,840
Hello.

409
00:24:38,680 --> 00:24:39,960
I'm good.

410
00:24:42,800 --> 00:24:44,080
Really?

411
00:24:46,480 --> 00:24:47,920
Just like that?

412
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:53,680
[James]
Tuesday. Fine.

413
00:24:53,720 --> 00:24:54,960
I'll be out of here.

414
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:17,680
Visibility is turning to shit out there!

415
00:25:17,760 --> 00:25:21,400
We checked his route,
he abandoned his Ski-Doo.

416
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:22,360
[Ed]
What?

417
00:25:22,440 --> 00:25:24,320
It started up fine.
He is out there on foot.

418
00:25:24,400 --> 00:25:25,400
Where's his Ski-Doo?

419
00:25:25,480 --> 00:25:26,640
Didn't want to leave him stranded.

420
00:25:26,680 --> 00:25:28,680
We gotta call a plane for a real search.

421
00:25:28,760 --> 00:25:30,480
No way! No way!

422
00:25:30,520 --> 00:25:32,360
That'd mean we'd have
to wait until morning.

423
00:25:32,400 --> 00:25:34,880
No, we do this ourselves,
and we do it now!

424
00:25:34,960 --> 00:25:37,000
I'm not losing a man!

425
00:25:37,040 --> 00:25:38,280
I'm going out there now.

426
00:25:38,320 --> 00:25:39,880
I'll go with you.

427
00:25:50,040 --> 00:25:51,120
[door slamming]

428
00:25:55,200 --> 00:25:56,880
Jesus.

429
00:25:56,920 --> 00:25:58,640
House!

430
00:26:00,760 --> 00:26:03,480
You had everybody's
panties in a knot, man.

431
00:26:03,560 --> 00:26:05,920
Hey, are you all right?

432
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:07,920
I'm... I'm okay.

433
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:10,760
I-I don't think this works.

434
00:26:10,800 --> 00:26:12,320
[device beeping]

435
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:16,480
According to this thing,
you walked 300 miles.

436
00:26:16,560 --> 00:26:17,800
[Abby]
We looked for you.

437
00:26:17,840 --> 00:26:19,120
[James]
So you got lost. I mean, what happened?

438
00:26:19,160 --> 00:26:20,880
- Hot tea.
- Welcome back, man.

439
00:26:20,960 --> 00:26:23,800
You gotta stay in contact, all right?

440
00:26:23,880 --> 00:26:25,280
Let somebody know where you're going.

441
00:26:25,360 --> 00:26:26,800
Standard procedure.

442
00:26:26,880 --> 00:26:29,880
And never, ever turn your walkie off.

443
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:30,840
It wasn't working.

444
00:26:30,920 --> 00:26:34,280
It was just screeching at me.

445
00:26:40,600 --> 00:26:44,600
Sorry. I'm gonna go lie down.

446
00:26:51,760 --> 00:26:54,080
That boy has got big eye.

447
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:57,040
He hasn't been out here long enough.

448
00:26:57,120 --> 00:26:58,480
He'll be fine.

449
00:26:58,520 --> 00:27:00,560
[tapping on keyboard]

450
00:27:02,960 --> 00:27:05,200
[James]
They're calling it a promotion.

451
00:27:05,240 --> 00:27:07,640
[Elliot]
Can they even do this?

452
00:27:07,720 --> 00:27:09,440
<i>Of course they can.</i>

453
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:11,560
You don't like the message,
you get a new messenger.

454
00:27:11,640 --> 00:27:13,800
I'm gonna quit.

455
00:27:13,840 --> 00:27:16,000
You should stay on.

456
00:27:16,080 --> 00:27:18,200
Take some notes on this new guy.

457
00:27:20,120 --> 00:27:22,840
You're giving up pretty easy.

458
00:27:24,320 --> 00:27:29,840
Look, man, I've been reporting
on this stuff a long time.

459
00:27:33,280 --> 00:27:36,960
People just don't want to deal with it.

460
00:27:37,040 --> 00:27:38,600
It's tiring.

461
00:27:40,480 --> 00:27:42,800
[woman moaning]

462
00:27:46,280 --> 00:27:49,400
[man grunting]

463
00:27:55,760 --> 00:27:59,320
<i># I won't tell you
I don't need you tonight #</i>

464
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:02,440
<i># Won't pretend I ain't burning inside #</i>

465
00:28:02,480 --> 00:28:07,600
<i># Your skin glowing soft
in the silver moonlight #</i>

466
00:28:07,680 --> 00:28:10,160
That was intense.

467
00:28:16,080 --> 00:28:19,400
What's up with you?

468
00:28:19,480 --> 00:28:22,720
I'm leaving.

469
00:28:22,800 --> 00:28:25,200
They're pulling me off the project.

470
00:28:26,920 --> 00:28:28,920
I didn't know if you knew.

471
00:28:37,240 --> 00:28:39,280
Why weren't you at that meeting today?

472
00:28:42,240 --> 00:28:46,120
I'm gonna recommend that
they shut the project down.

473
00:28:46,200 --> 00:28:48,120
I don't think they can get those rigs out.

474
00:28:48,200 --> 00:28:50,960
Jim, it's too late for that.

475
00:28:56,200 --> 00:28:58,880
[footsteps]

476
00:29:02,040 --> 00:29:03,040
How's Maxwell?

477
00:29:03,120 --> 00:29:05,600
Try to get some food in him, will you?

478
00:29:05,680 --> 00:29:07,920
Work some of your magic.

479
00:29:23,600 --> 00:29:28,840
I figure, take him out here first.

480
00:29:28,880 --> 00:29:32,000
We tell him we're gonna get
the rigs in here in nine days.

481
00:29:32,080 --> 00:29:34,800
They're gonna stay until March,
I don't know, 19th,

482
00:29:34,840 --> 00:29:37,840
and then we're gonna get them over
to the Northeastern site.

483
00:29:37,920 --> 00:29:40,720
I mean, you know, we just tell him that,
you know, like it's a done deal.

484
00:29:40,800 --> 00:29:41,960
Yeah, well, you tell him that, Ed.

485
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:42,960
I mean, Jesus.

486
00:29:43,040 --> 00:29:44,800
I'll handle him.

487
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:47,120
Is this...

488
00:29:47,200 --> 00:29:50,520
Is this Maxwell flagging these sits?

489
00:29:50,600 --> 00:29:52,920
What is he, sniffing glue out here or what?

490
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:55,320
I don't know what this is.

491
00:29:55,400 --> 00:29:57,400
Jesus.

492
00:29:57,480 --> 00:29:59,600
We're gonna have to check
all these sites now.

493
00:29:59,640 --> 00:30:00,880
Yeah, okay.

494
00:30:00,920 --> 00:30:02,800
Lee, this is going to be you.

495
00:30:02,840 --> 00:30:04,120
All of them.

496
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:08,120
Will do.

497
00:30:08,200 --> 00:30:11,120
Excuse me.

498
00:30:11,200 --> 00:30:13,200
You're gonna have your
work cut out for you.

499
00:30:13,280 --> 00:30:15,920
Yeah, I think this is going
to take more than one of us.

500
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:17,680
Better you than me.

501
00:30:17,720 --> 00:30:20,680
<i>Oh, nature calls.</i>

502
00:30:20,760 --> 00:30:23,240
So, Hoffman, what do you figure,

503
00:30:23,280 --> 00:30:25,200
we bring the rigs in here on rollagon?

504
00:30:25,240 --> 00:30:27,200
Is that gonna work?

505
00:30:27,280 --> 00:30:30,960
Uh, the tundra is barely frozen.

506
00:30:31,040 --> 00:30:35,280
It won't support the weight
of those vehicles.

507
00:30:35,360 --> 00:30:36,840
Well, now...

508
00:30:36,920 --> 00:30:39,080
[zipping]

509
00:30:39,120 --> 00:30:43,320
how do you propose we get
the equipment in here, then?

510
00:30:43,400 --> 00:30:45,800
Maybe you won't get it in.

511
00:30:45,880 --> 00:30:49,120
Maybe you're gonna have
to reconsider your plans.

512
00:30:49,200 --> 00:30:51,320
That's the wrong answer.

513
00:30:51,400 --> 00:30:53,920
<i>It's the CO2 feeding back up.</i>

514
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:56,040
As the ground warms,

515
00:30:56,080 --> 00:30:58,040
permafrost, all this organic material

516
00:30:58,120 --> 00:31:00,680
that's been frozen for thousands
of years is thawing,

517
00:31:00,720 --> 00:31:02,360
which accelerates the warming.

518
00:31:02,440 --> 00:31:04,600
It's exponential,
what we're talking about here.

519
00:31:04,680 --> 00:31:07,800
What is this, some
global warming bullshit?

520
00:31:07,880 --> 00:31:10,600
I mean, don't you think
it's a little late in the day

521
00:31:10,640 --> 00:31:12,040
to be having that particular debate?

522
00:31:12,080 --> 00:31:14,480
It's not a debate
about global warming, Ed.

523
00:31:14,520 --> 00:31:16,480
It's just what we're
dealing with out here now.

524
00:31:16,560 --> 00:31:18,680
Yeah, well, fortunately,

525
00:31:18,760 --> 00:31:22,240
I don't have to listen to you anymore.

526
00:31:22,320 --> 00:31:24,000
You asked.

527
00:31:24,080 --> 00:31:25,880
Just making conversation.

528
00:32:14,320 --> 00:32:17,200
<i>[James]
"Empathy with the land.</i>

529
00:32:17,280 --> 00:32:19,680
<i>Is this learned in childhood?"</i>

530
00:32:31,040 --> 00:32:33,000
<i>"The land is changed.</i>

531
00:32:33,040 --> 00:32:38,120
<i>"The biosphere turned,
become unfamiliar and erratic.</i>

532
00:32:38,160 --> 00:32:39,920
<i>"I would say vengeful,</i>

533
00:32:39,960 --> 00:32:41,320
<i>"but nature's indifferent to us.</i>

534
00:32:41,360 --> 00:32:44,840
<i>"We fight for our survival, not nature's.</i>

535
00:32:44,920 --> 00:32:48,080
<i>"There's a fierceness in the wind
I've never felt before.</i>

536
00:32:48,160 --> 00:32:52,240
<i>"Something is being unleashed
from the softening permafrost.</i>

537
00:32:52,280 --> 00:32:55,920
<i>"Why do we despise the world
that give us life?</i>

538
00:32:55,960 --> 00:32:57,480
<i>Why so alienated?"</i>

539
00:33:01,520 --> 00:33:03,600
<i>"Why wouldn't the wilderness fight us,</i>

540
00:33:03,680 --> 00:33:07,280
<i>"like any other organism
would fend off a virus?</i>

541
00:33:07,320 --> 00:33:11,000
<i>"The world we grew up in
is changed forever.</i>

542
00:33:11,080 --> 00:33:15,120
<i>There is no way home. "</i>

543
00:33:17,200 --> 00:33:18,680
<i>"Is there something beyond science</i>

544
00:33:18,760 --> 00:33:20,760
<i>"that is happening out here?</i>

545
00:33:20,840 --> 00:33:24,680
<i>"What if the very thing
we were here to pull out of the ground</i>

546
00:33:24,720 --> 00:33:29,040
<i>"were to rise willingly and confront us?</i>

547
00:33:29,120 --> 00:33:32,240
<i>"What would that look like?</i>

548
00:33:32,280 --> 00:33:36,560
<i>"This is the last winter.</i>

549
00:33:36,640 --> 00:33:38,520
<i>Total collapse. "</i>

550
00:33:40,080 --> 00:33:43,200
<i>"Hope dies."</i>

551
00:34:01,040 --> 00:34:02,320
[rumbling]

552
00:34:08,240 --> 00:34:10,680
[rumbling]

553
00:34:14,440 --> 00:34:16,640
[wind and rumbling]

554
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:23,360
[wind and rumbling]

555
00:34:23,440 --> 00:34:24,880
[water dripping]

556
00:34:27,160 --> 00:34:29,760
[wind whipping]

557
00:34:38,480 --> 00:34:41,440
[rain falling]

558
00:35:06,560 --> 00:35:10,160
[trampoline squeaking]

559
00:35:23,600 --> 00:35:25,520
[rain pelting roof]

560
00:35:49,560 --> 00:35:52,440
[rain continues]

561
00:35:59,360 --> 00:36:00,400
[gasps]

562
00:36:00,480 --> 00:36:02,080
Something happening, Dawn.

563
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:03,480
[Motor]
That's brilliant! Do that again!

564
00:36:03,560 --> 00:36:05,240
<i>Very Twilight Zone.</i>

565
00:36:06,520 --> 00:36:08,480
Would either of you like
to comment on the fact

566
00:36:08,560 --> 00:36:12,200
that it's fucking raining out,
February in the Arctic?

567
00:36:12,240 --> 00:36:15,040
I'm freaking, man.

568
00:36:15,120 --> 00:36:17,840
<i>- [Dawn] Uginaca.
- What's that, Dawn?</i>

569
00:36:17,880 --> 00:36:22,840
Well, it means like a familiar friend
acting strangely.

570
00:36:22,920 --> 00:36:24,560
It's how we speak of weather.

571
00:36:24,640 --> 00:36:27,480
It gets worse every year.

572
00:36:53,960 --> 00:36:57,520
[heart beating]

573
00:36:59,560 --> 00:37:01,000
[Motor]
What's happening?

574
00:37:01,080 --> 00:37:03,280
What do you say about it, Hoffman?

575
00:37:03,320 --> 00:37:05,000
[Hoffman]
The climate's changing exponentially.

576
00:37:05,040 --> 00:37:06,760
It's collapsing. It's altering.

577
00:37:06,800 --> 00:37:08,760
[Motor]
I'm talking about right now,
today, what happened?

578
00:37:08,840 --> 00:37:10,640
That's what I'm talking about, today.

579
00:37:10,720 --> 00:37:12,000
It was rain.

580
00:37:12,080 --> 00:37:15,320
For Christ's sake, the temperature's
already dropping back.

581
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:17,680
It was a fluke.

582
00:37:17,760 --> 00:37:19,440
Well?

583
00:37:19,480 --> 00:37:21,880
He's staring out the window.

584
00:37:21,960 --> 00:37:23,080
He say anything?

585
00:37:23,120 --> 00:37:24,200
No.

586
00:37:24,280 --> 00:37:26,240
Did you tell him I said it was dinnertime?

587
00:37:26,320 --> 00:37:28,720
Yep.

588
00:37:28,800 --> 00:37:29,920
Send him home, Ed.

589
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:31,000
That's what I say.

590
00:37:31,080 --> 00:37:32,200
He's not going anywhere.

591
00:37:32,240 --> 00:37:34,000
Well, if he doesn't eat, he can't work.

592
00:37:34,080 --> 00:37:36,280
I realize... Jesus Christ.

593
00:37:36,360 --> 00:37:38,680
Can I get a little fucking positivity here?

594
00:37:38,760 --> 00:37:40,440
[scoffs]

595
00:37:41,520 --> 00:37:43,240
And wipe your face.

596
00:37:43,280 --> 00:37:44,400
You're pathetic.

597
00:37:48,160 --> 00:37:49,840
You do realize that there are restrictions

598
00:37:49,920 --> 00:37:51,960
on alcohol consumptions
at this station, don't you?

599
00:37:52,040 --> 00:37:52,920
[laughing]

600
00:37:53,000 --> 00:37:55,760
And what about you?
Would you pass a piss test?

601
00:37:55,800 --> 00:37:57,480
And where do you think you're going?

602
00:37:57,520 --> 00:37:59,120
Let him try, Ed.

603
00:37:59,200 --> 00:38:01,160
Yeah. House likes him.

604
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:02,160
[knock on door]

605
00:38:04,040 --> 00:38:05,600
May I come in?

606
00:38:05,680 --> 00:38:07,000
[Maxwell]
Yeah.

607
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:13,960
I brought you this.

608
00:38:28,440 --> 00:38:30,800
What happened out there yesterday?

609
00:38:30,880 --> 00:38:32,200
When we lost you?

610
00:38:34,320 --> 00:38:35,240
I don't know.

611
00:38:37,800 --> 00:38:39,280
<i>Out by the KIK well...</i>

612
00:38:40,720 --> 00:38:41,840
it's haunted.

613
00:38:41,920 --> 00:38:44,520
All right. Just... take a deep breath

614
00:38:44,560 --> 00:38:46,800
down on that one there, Maxwell.

615
00:38:46,840 --> 00:38:49,440
We shouldn't be here.

616
00:38:49,520 --> 00:38:52,000
We're grave robbers.

617
00:38:52,080 --> 00:38:53,920
It's coming up from the ground.

618
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:54,920
Ghosts.

619
00:38:56,040 --> 00:38:58,160
I mean, what is oil anyway but fossils?

620
00:38:58,240 --> 00:39:00,680
Plants and animals from...

621
00:39:00,720 --> 00:39:03,080
whatever... millions of years ago.

622
00:39:03,120 --> 00:39:05,520
Listen. Maxwell.

623
00:39:05,560 --> 00:39:06,720
That's...

624
00:39:08,640 --> 00:39:10,080
Maybe...

625
00:39:10,160 --> 00:39:12,680
this has gotten to be
a little too much for you.

626
00:39:14,480 --> 00:39:16,520
It's pretty intense out here.

627
00:39:19,280 --> 00:39:21,240
You can go home.

628
00:39:22,520 --> 00:39:24,200
Have you thought of that?

629
00:39:36,920 --> 00:39:37,920
I can't.

630
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:39,760
My... my parents would kill me.

631
00:39:44,520 --> 00:39:46,120
Your parents aren't going to kill you.

632
00:39:47,240 --> 00:39:50,280
It was my father's
idea for me to be here.

633
00:39:50,320 --> 00:39:55,160
Satisfy my love of the outdoors
by drilling for oil with Uncle Ed.

634
00:39:55,240 --> 00:39:59,280
Well, maybe your father would listen
if you explained to him.

635
00:39:59,320 --> 00:40:01,040
Have you thought about that?

636
00:40:03,120 --> 00:40:04,960
Man...

637
00:40:05,040 --> 00:40:07,160
eat some food.

638
00:40:07,240 --> 00:40:09,000
I'm telling you!
There's something out there

639
00:40:09,040 --> 00:40:11,240
<i>- that's trying to drive us out of here!
- Okay...</i>

640
00:40:11,280 --> 00:40:13,040
It's like a force, fighting back!

641
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:16,040
- Maxwell, you gotta...
- No! People need to know! Isn't that your job?

642
00:40:16,120 --> 00:40:18,560
To let people know what the fuck
they're supposed to do here?

643
00:40:18,640 --> 00:40:19,600
What the hell is going on?

644
00:40:19,680 --> 00:40:21,200
- Tell them! Tell them what you know!
- Hey!

645
00:40:21,280 --> 00:40:23,600
- Calm down! You, get the fuck out of here!
- You know what's happening!

646
00:40:23,640 --> 00:40:25,320
You know! You've said things!

647
00:40:25,360 --> 00:40:27,280
- You know what's going on...
- Calm down!

648
00:40:29,920 --> 00:40:31,560
[Ed, softly]
You gonna calm the fuck down?

649
00:40:31,600 --> 00:40:32,560
[door slams]

650
00:40:32,600 --> 00:40:34,160
Yes, sir.

651
00:40:34,240 --> 00:40:35,200
Just need...

652
00:40:37,240 --> 00:40:38,200
I need to rest.

653
00:40:39,600 --> 00:40:40,880
Sorry.

654
00:40:44,400 --> 00:40:46,640
[wind blows]

655
00:40:49,680 --> 00:40:53,160
[dripping water]

656
00:41:16,400 --> 00:41:17,480
He's resting.

657
00:41:19,600 --> 00:41:21,280
Dawn's got him on something.

658
00:41:24,440 --> 00:41:26,000
What the hell was that in there?

659
00:41:28,360 --> 00:41:30,920
I got Maxwell out here, you know.

660
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:33,440
Told his old man how good
it would be for him.

661
00:41:34,400 --> 00:41:35,680
[sighs]

662
00:41:37,800 --> 00:41:40,640
Known that kid since the day he was born.

663
00:41:40,720 --> 00:41:42,320
I know, Ed.

664
00:41:42,400 --> 00:41:43,440
It's Hoffman!

665
00:41:48,480 --> 00:41:52,520
I have no idea how you ended up in
the sack with that guy.

666
00:41:52,560 --> 00:41:53,880
But I gotta tell ya,

667
00:41:53,960 --> 00:41:55,280
I consider it a security breach.

668
00:41:55,360 --> 00:41:58,760
We had nothing to hide, Ed.

669
00:41:58,840 --> 00:42:00,360
Everything is by the book.

670
00:42:00,400 --> 00:42:02,760
He works for North.

671
00:42:05,240 --> 00:42:07,560
Every report he does goes through us.

672
00:42:09,360 --> 00:42:11,600
I think you made a big mistake
transferring him out of here.

673
00:42:11,680 --> 00:42:14,440
I'll be damned if I'm gonna let him
or anybody else fuck this up for me!

674
00:42:14,480 --> 00:42:18,000
I had his confidence.
I had my eye on him.

675
00:42:18,080 --> 00:42:19,240
[deep sigh]

676
00:42:21,800 --> 00:42:23,000
You let me down, Abby.

677
00:42:23,080 --> 00:42:25,280
I did not, Ed.

678
00:42:27,480 --> 00:42:29,160
I mean personally.

679
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:35,400
I guess that's over with.

680
00:42:40,600 --> 00:42:41,960
Yeah, it is.

681
00:42:43,760 --> 00:42:44,680
Good night.

682
00:42:47,640 --> 00:42:49,880
Sure hope you don't like
the new guy as much.

683
00:42:53,520 --> 00:42:55,800
- Who you got?
- Hmm.

684
00:42:55,880 --> 00:42:56,960
Marshowitz.

685
00:42:58,000 --> 00:42:59,480
[door closes]

686
00:42:59,560 --> 00:43:00,520
Abby.

687
00:43:02,240 --> 00:43:03,680
I'm tired.

688
00:43:06,880 --> 00:43:08,800
Maxwell...

689
00:43:08,880 --> 00:43:11,240
saw something out there.
Something's going on here.

690
00:43:13,280 --> 00:43:14,760
- [unzipping]
- [sighs]

691
00:43:14,840 --> 00:43:18,960
Don't think you need
to get involved with Maxwell.

692
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:21,920
We'll take care of him.

693
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:23,440
That sounds ominous.

694
00:43:25,200 --> 00:43:28,120
You know, you're getting awfully vocal
about what we're doing up here.

695
00:43:30,120 --> 00:43:31,920
It's not gonna work with Pollack.

696
00:43:34,480 --> 00:43:36,880
You should've just signed
those impact reports.

697
00:43:36,920 --> 00:43:39,120
Pollack has no idea
what's going on out here.

698
00:43:39,160 --> 00:43:41,840
<i>- Oh, and you do?
- No, I don't, either.</i>

699
00:43:41,920 --> 00:43:44,480
That's why I'd like to
take a giant step backwards

700
00:43:44,560 --> 00:43:47,920
and get some people up here
who can figure out what is going on.

701
00:43:50,600 --> 00:43:52,280
You know your deal with North prohibits you

702
00:43:52,360 --> 00:43:55,640
from saying anything
about this to anyone.

703
00:43:55,720 --> 00:43:58,000
What's that supposed to mean?

704
00:43:58,080 --> 00:44:00,080
Just need to make that clear.

705
00:44:03,080 --> 00:44:04,680
Abby!

706
00:44:04,720 --> 00:44:07,160
You don't feel that something is off here?

707
00:44:11,200 --> 00:44:12,880
Listen, Abby.

708
00:44:12,960 --> 00:44:14,320
You can make a real difference here.

709
00:44:14,400 --> 00:44:16,160
Draw a line in the sand.

710
00:44:16,240 --> 00:44:17,280
If they shut this project down,

711
00:44:17,360 --> 00:44:19,680
the others could be called into question.

712
00:44:19,760 --> 00:44:21,960
You could be part of
a change for the better.

713
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:24,920
Take your case to North, if you need to.

714
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:28,680
At this station, we're fighting
to get those rigs in.

715
00:44:28,720 --> 00:44:32,840
Whatever it takes, and on schedule.

716
00:44:32,880 --> 00:44:35,240
What's been going on with us
these last three weeks?

717
00:44:45,920 --> 00:44:47,160
I gotta sleep.

718
00:44:59,160 --> 00:45:01,480
[snoring]

719
00:45:06,480 --> 00:45:08,040
[turns off camera, removes tape]

720
00:45:11,760 --> 00:45:13,800
[Ed, snoring]

721
00:45:15,840 --> 00:45:18,200
[snoring]

722
00:45:25,600 --> 00:45:28,200
[wind howling]

723
00:45:30,600 --> 00:45:34,720
[wind blowing]

724
00:46:05,080 --> 00:46:06,800
[Ed]
This is on the fritz, too.

725
00:46:06,840 --> 00:46:09,560
We gotta do something to get these systems
up and running, Motor.

726
00:46:09,640 --> 00:46:11,080
I fix stuff around here.

727
00:46:11,160 --> 00:46:12,840
Two hours later, it's broke again.

728
00:46:12,880 --> 00:46:16,640
Maybe we need to get somebody
down here who could figure this shit out.

729
00:46:16,720 --> 00:46:18,760
Hey. Look at this.

730
00:46:20,160 --> 00:46:21,440
How's he doing?

731
00:46:26,480 --> 00:46:27,800
What is this now?

732
00:46:52,680 --> 00:46:54,000
[Motor]
There's my camera, man!

733
00:46:54,040 --> 00:46:56,800
We should thaw the fucker out
and see if he shot anything with it.

734
00:47:23,840 --> 00:47:25,520
[engine stops]

735
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:09,640
[wings fluttering]

736
00:48:16,040 --> 00:48:18,880
[squawking]

737
00:48:44,200 --> 00:48:45,880
[engine stops]

738
00:48:56,240 --> 00:48:57,400
God damn it!

739
00:49:02,400 --> 00:49:03,320
Where was he?

740
00:49:03,400 --> 00:49:05,160
[Lee]
Up by the KIK well.

741
00:49:06,160 --> 00:49:07,600
You should have send him home, Ed.

742
00:49:07,680 --> 00:49:09,840
You should have sent him the fuck home!

743
00:49:09,920 --> 00:49:12,440
We'd better call and report this.

744
00:49:12,520 --> 00:49:14,600
- Radio's dead.
- [Ed] We wait until morning!

745
00:49:16,080 --> 00:49:17,760
Foster's flying in here with what's-his-name.

746
00:49:17,840 --> 00:49:19,520
We get Maxwell flown out by Gary.

747
00:49:19,600 --> 00:49:20,760
That's final!

748
00:49:36,960 --> 00:49:39,200
<i>[Maxwell, recorded]
Ever since I got here,</i>

749
00:49:39,280 --> 00:49:42,000
<i>I could tell that there
was something wrong.</i>

750
00:49:42,040 --> 00:49:46,560
<i>Not the Job. Not the cold.
Not being isolated.</i>

751
00:49:46,640 --> 00:49:49,560
<i>But feeling... how?</i>

752
00:49:49,640 --> 00:49:51,960
<i>I'm telling you.</i>

753
00:49:52,040 --> 00:49:53,840
<i>I've seen something out in the snow.</i>

754
00:49:56,080 --> 00:49:57,680
<i>I want to show you.</i>

755
00:49:59,800 --> 00:50:01,840
Jesus. What's he doing?

756
00:50:03,760 --> 00:50:05,000
<i>[Maxwell, recorded] Do you see it?</i>

757
00:50:06,960 --> 00:50:08,200
<i>Did you see it?</i>

758
00:50:10,600 --> 00:50:12,520
<i>[shivering breath]
Did you see it?</i>

759
00:50:14,200 --> 00:50:15,520
<i>[wind blows]</i>

760
00:50:15,600 --> 00:50:16,880
<i>Up ahead. They're out now.</i>

761
00:50:19,680 --> 00:50:21,920
<i>Listen! Listen! That!</i>

762
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:24,440
<i>- [wind, crackling]
- It...</i>

763
00:50:24,520 --> 00:50:25,720
<i>Dad, do you hear that?</i>

764
00:50:27,160 --> 00:50:28,360
<i>Listen!</i>

765
00:50:28,400 --> 00:50:30,760
<i>[wind, crackling]</i>

766
00:50:30,800 --> 00:50:33,360
<i>Do you see it, Dad?</i>

767
00:50:33,440 --> 00:50:35,520
<i>They're out there!</i>

768
00:50:35,600 --> 00:50:36,920
<i>They're right out there!</i>

769
00:50:40,080 --> 00:50:41,720
<i>[shivering]
You see... you see that?</i>

770
00:50:44,240 --> 00:50:46,640
<i>Do you see it? Do you see it?</i>

771
00:50:46,720 --> 00:50:47,720
[gasps]

772
00:50:54,680 --> 00:50:56,240
All right. That's it.

773
00:50:56,320 --> 00:50:57,680
[tape ejects]

774
00:50:57,760 --> 00:50:59,400
[Abby]
Ed...

775
00:50:59,480 --> 00:51:00,440
Ed!

